Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "TcpClient and NetworkStream do not react to network changes" (#1347) at xamarin/xamarin-android
Events.RelatedBody:
### Steps to Reproduce

1. Build and install the attached project
2. Note the logcat output indicating (on a 5 second loop) that the TcpClient is connected, and its network stream is read-writable
3. Put the device into airplane mode

[NetworkStreamBug.zip](https://github.com/xamarin/xamarin-android/files/1766265/NetworkStreamBug.zip)

### Expected Behavior

The TcpClient would no longer show a connected status, and/or the NetworkStream would either have CanRead/CanWrite be false or throw an exception when a read or write is attempted (not applicable to this demo project, but I have a more sophisticated project that shows how writing stuff seems to write into a void never to be seen again if you are interested.  It just requires more setup)

### Actual Behavior

The TcpClient stays in a connected state, and reads / writes from NetworkStream succeed despite actually doing nothing.  Furthermore, on connection restoration this situation continues.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "[Enhancement] Add Maximum(Width/Height)Request to VisualElement" (#2000) at xamarin/Xamarin.Forms
Events.RelatedBody:
### Description
It would be nice to have counterparts to the existing Minimum(Width/Height)Request properties.

Maximum(Width/Height) should do the following calculation:
VisualElement.(Width/Height) = Max(Maximum(Width/Height)Request, VisualElement.(Width/Height));

### Expected Behaviour
The VisualElement should select the maximum size if it's measure is smaller; otherwise grow as the measure requires.

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "Xamarin.Mac Binding Library project does not support "Full" framework" (#3608) at xamarin/xamarin-macios
Events.RelatedBody:
### Steps to Reproduce

1. Create a new Xamarin.Mac "Bindings Library"
2. Open up the properties for the bindings project
3. Set Build > General > Target Framework to "Xamarin.Mac Full"
4. Add a Cocoa App and set its target framework to "Xamarin.Mac Full"
5. Add a reference on the Cocoa App to the bindings library
5. Compile (broken!)

### Expected Behavior
You should be able to create a bindings library for either "modern" or "full" frameworks, *and* compile them.

### Actual Behavior
It only works for the "modern" framework.
